{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":25284,"record_hash":"sha256:17feb5fd68bba7b3f96d0eb6a34a6ff5f24b14763f735b5167026ecee9a9be58","timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:50:40.073Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n- [crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs:287): Batch `SetAdd` logs `serde_json::to_string(members)?`, i.e. only the batch payload. Existing single `set_add` logs the full post-mutation set via `encode_set_values_by_metadata_id` at [crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/sets.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/sets.rs:181). That makes `metadata_log.value` inconsistent for the same operation depending on API path. Serialization currently reads current metadata, so this is mainly a logging/replay/audit compatibility risk. The new test at [crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/mod.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/mod.rs:673) does not inspect logs.\\n\\n- [crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs:70): `apply_edits` promises one transaction, but the added test only covers a happy path final read. A regression that commits the first edit before a later `TypeMismatch` would not be caught. A small behavior test should apply a valid edit followed by an invalid/type-mismatched edit and assert neither the metadata nor `metadata_log` changed.\\n\\nI ran the targeted tests after an initial bad cargo filter: `cargo test -p git-meta-lib test_apply_edits`, `cargo test -p git-meta-lib test_list_push_logs_only_pushed_entry`, and `cargo test -p git-meta-lib merge_set_union`; all passed, with existing dead-code warnings.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:50:40.073Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n- [crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs:287): Batch `SetAdd` logs `serde_json::to_string(members)?`, i.e. only the batch payload. Existing single `set_add` logs the full post-mutation set via `encode_set_values_by_metadata_id` at [crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/sets.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/sets.rs:181). That makes `metadata_log.value` inconsistent for the same operation depending on API path. Serialization currently reads current metadata, so this is mainly a logging/replay/audit compatibility risk. The new test at [crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/mod.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/mod.rs:673) does not inspect logs.\\n\\n- [crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs:70): `apply_edits` promises one transaction, but the added test only covers a happy path final read. A regression that commits the first edit before a later `TypeMismatch` would not be caught. A small behavior test should apply a valid edit followed by an invalid/type-mismatched edit and assert neither the metadata nor `metadata_log` changed.\\n\\nI ran the targeted tests after an initial bad cargo filter: `cargo test -p git-meta-lib test_apply_edits`, `cargo test -p git-meta-lib test_list_push_logs_only_pushed_entry`, and `cargo test -p git-meta-lib merge_set_union`; all passed, with existing dead-code warnings.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>"}]}}}